There are different departments:

* Reception
* Laboratory
* Doctor
* Medical Records
* Pharmacy

Each department has one job.

Your app works the same way.

---

# Our System Architecture

```text
                USER

                  │

                  ▼

        📱 Mobile App (Flutter)

                  │

                  ▼

        🌐 Backend (FastAPI)

                  │

     ┌────────────┼────────────┐

     ▼            ▼            ▼

🗄 PostgreSQL    📂 S3      🔍 OCR

Database       Storage     Reads PDF

                  │

                  ▼

            🤖 OpenAI

                  │

                  ▼

          AI Explanation

                  │

                  ▼

          Mobile App Shows Results
```

Every part has one responsibility.

---

# Step 1 – Mobile App

This is what the user sees.

The mobile app is responsible for:

* Login
* Uploading reports
* Viewing history
* Comparing reports
* Reading AI explanations

It **does not** process the report itself.

Think of it as the **reception desk**.

---

# Step 2 – Backend

The backend is the manager.

Whenever the mobile app needs something, it asks the backend.

Example:

User uploads a PDF.

The app sends it to the backend.

The backend decides:

* Where to store it
* When to run OCR
* When to call AI
* What data to save

---

# Step 3 – Cloud Storage (S3)

Blood reports are PDF files.

They should not be stored inside the database.

Instead:

Store them in cloud storage.

Example:

```text
reports/

Alice_Report_July.pdf

Bob_Report_March.pdf

Charlie_Report_Jan.pdf
```

The database simply remembers **where** the file is stored.

---

# Step 4 – OCR

OCR means:

**Optical Character Recognition**

Its job is simple.

Convert:

```text
PDF

↓

Image

↓

Text
```

Example:

The report contains:

```text
Hemoglobin

13.2
```

OCR extracts:

```text
Hemoglobin = 13.2
```

That's all.

It doesn't understand medicine.

It only reads text.

---

# Step 5 – OCR Review

OCR isn't perfect.

Maybe it reads:

18

instead of

13

So before AI runs:

The user reviews the extracted values.

Example:

```text
Hemoglobin

13.2

[ Edit ]

HbA1c

5.9

[ Edit ]
```

This improves accuracy and builds trust.

---

# Step 6 – Database

The database stores structured information.

Example:

```text
User

↓

Patient

↓

Report

↓

Blood Test Values

↓

Upload Date
```

Notice:

It stores the numbers, not the PDF itself.

Example:

```text
Hemoglobin = 13.2

HbA1c = 5.9

Vitamin D = 22
```

This makes it easy to compare reports later.

---

# Step 7 – AI

After OCR is confirmed:

The backend sends the values to AI.

Example:

```text
Hemoglobin

13.2

HbA1c

5.9

Vitamin D

18
```

The AI returns:

> "Your hemoglobin is within the reference range shown on the report. Your Vitamin D is below the reference range. Consider discussing these results with your healthcare professional."

The AI explains.

It does **not** diagnose.

---

# Step 8 – Save Everything

Now the system stores:

* User
* PDF location
* Blood values
* AI summary
* Upload date

Nothing is lost.

---

# Step 9 – History

When the user opens History:

The app asks:

```text
Backend

↓

Database

↓

Return all reports
```

The app simply displays them.

---

# Step 10 – Compare Reports

The database already has:

```text
Jan

Hemoglobin

11.2

July

Hemoglobin

13.4
```

The app compares them.

Example:

```text
11.2

↓

13.4

Improved
```

No AI is needed for this step.

---

# The Complete Flow

```text
User Uploads Report

↓

Mobile App

↓

Backend

↓

Save PDF to Cloud

↓

OCR Reads Report

↓

User Reviews Values

↓

AI Explains Report

↓

Database Saves Data

↓

History Updated

↓

Compare Reports Available
```

This is your complete MVP architecture.

---

# Who Does What?

| Component     | Responsibility              |
| ------------- | --------------------------- |
| Mobile App    | User interface              |
| Backend       | Coordinates everything      |
| Cloud Storage | Stores PDFs                 |
| OCR           | Extracts text from reports  |
| Database      | Stores structured data      |
| AI            | Explains blood test results |

Notice that each component has **one clear job**.

---

# What Happens if OCR Fails?

Suppose OCR misses a value.

The app should allow the user to:

* Edit the value
* Add missing values manually
* Continue

The app should never block the user completely.

---

# Why This Architecture is Good

✅ Easy to maintain

✅ Easy to upgrade

✅ Easy to scale

✅ Secure

✅ Components can improve independently

For example, if you later replace the OCR provider, the rest of the app doesn't need major changes.

